_From @ventsislav-georgiev on October 18, 2016 13:25_

The **ES6** `arrow syntax` preserves `this` to be the parent scope. However, in VSCode node debugging the on hover provider shows the `bind`-ed value of `this`, which is really confusing while debugging.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5616486/19479439/69c70a20-954f-11e6-9df3-351e68782a54.png)

> Note: that evaluation or `console.log` in the debug console shows the correct value of `this`.

**VSCode version:**
1.6.1

**Node Debug version:**
1.6.10

**Code to reproduce**

``` js
(function() { 
    console.log(`parentScope: ${this.fake}`);

    (() => { 
        console.log(`childScope: ${this.fake}`);
        debugger;
    }).call({ innerFake: "innerFakeValue" }); 

}).call({ fake: "fakeValue" });
```

_Copied from original issue: Microsoft/vscode-node-debug#103_

- VSCode Version: 1.6.1
- OS Version:  OSX El Capitan (10.11.6)

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Stack a destructured object at the top of the `render()` method in a React component.
2. Write some JSX in the `return()` block of the render method.  The JSX will be mostly orange, as opposed to having a distinction between elements and attributes like one would expect:

![badhighlighting](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7085141/19491351/3d3fad66-9538-11e6-8c2c-a1db81f4103e.png)

Sample code to reproduce:

``` javascript
export class Test extends Component {
  render () {
    const {
      test,
      test2,
      test3 } = this.props

    return (
      <div className={test}>
      </div>
    )
  }
}
```
